Everything interesting is in the CrewAI class.

Note that for system names, ShipSystem::SystemIdToName is very helpful.

System hacking levels (stored in ShipSystem.iHackEffect) are (my constant names):
0=HACK_NONE
1=HACK_STANDBY (hacking system on, doors locked)
2=HACK_ACTIVE  (start button pressed)

Crew tasks are more inconvenient to find, my names are:
0=TASK_MANNING
1=TASK_REPAIR
2=TASK_FIGHT_FIRE
3=TASK_REPAIR_HULL_BREACH (though this may be wrong, seen in CrewAI::CheckForProblems)
4=TASK_IDLE               (not entirely sure, though CrewMember::ClearTask sets it)
5=TASK_DYING              (also not entirely clear, but it seems pretty likely)
6=TASK_HEALING
7=TASK_COMBAT
8=TASK_TELEPORTING        (not sure if this is standing on a teleporter, or all of boarding)

Note that mind-controlled crew use the standard intruder/crew AI.



CrewAI::CheckForHealing:

For each crew member, if all of:
    - the crew health is <25% (non-calm ship) or <99% (calm ship)
    - the medbay is working and isn't hacked
    - the medbay room is rated as safe (see CrewAI::DangerRating)
    - the crewmember isn't dying (as in, bDead==false)
Then path to the medbay.

If the health is low but the medbay is inaccessible, mark
the medbay as requested (this adjusts repair priorities).


CrewAI::DangerRating:

(Note this function returns 1 for safe and 0 for dangerous)

- If a room is an airlock and an airlock door is open, it's dangerous
- If health<25% and oxygen<10% it's dangerous, if we can suffocate (ie, except lanius)
- If fireCount>0 and health<20%, it's dangerous unless we're immune to fire
- If fireCount>=4 then it's dangerous unless we're immune to fire
- This room is the medbay, and it's being hacked


CrewAI::PrioritizeSystem:

0: Shields
1: Weapons, clonebay
2: Artillery
3: Oxygen
4: Engines, drones, piloting
5: Cloaking, mind control, hacking
6: Sensors, battery
7: Doors
8: Everything else

Medbay: 1 if it's requested (see CheckForHealing), 2 otherwise.

Teleporter: if an urgent teleport is demanded, priority 0 (!!).
If (I think? iTeleportRequest!=0) a teleport is requested, priority 1
Otherwise, priority 3


CrewAI::CheckForProblems:

Boarders get a single task each

A room with any number of fires (and more than 10% oxygen) gets two
tasks to put the fire out, plus a bonus task for it if two crewmembers
are currently attached to those tasks (though that bit is quite confusing).

A number of teleporting tasks, to match the iTeleportRequest variable.

Hull breaches get a task, one per room, plus a bonus task.


CrewAI::PrioritizeTask:

If a task is in a room marked as dangerous (see DangerRating), then it
gets a priority of 100.

For crew members that are bad at combat (<1x damage or <100hp), healing
and teleporting tasks also get a priority of 100, if not all of the crew
are bad at combat, and unless the combat/race override is set (see the end
of AttemptToAssign).

Teleporting tasks for crew with <50% health also get a priority of 100.
Otherwise, non-urgent teleporting is 32 if the teleporter is charged,
65 if the teleporter isn't charged, and in all cases urgent teleporting
is priority 0.

(assuming here that difficulty 2 is hard)

For manning tasks:

Piloting is 64
Shields are 67 on hard, else 65.
Engines are 65 on hard, else 67.
Weapons and artillery is 66
Oxygen is 68
Sensors is 69
Doors and cloaking is 70
Teleporter is 71
Medbay is 72
Anything else is 1000.

For repair tasks, use PrioritizeSystem + 48.
The exception is that if oxygen is below 25%, repairing
the oxygen system has priority 0. Also, shields is always
priority 1 (not 1+48, just 1).

Healing tasks has priority 0.

Fire fighting and combat tasks:
Use PrioritizeSystem + 16, or 24 (8+16) for rooms without a system.

For task ID=3 (likely repairing hull breaches):
Use PrioritizeSystem + 32, or 40 (8+32) for rooms without a system.


CrewAI::UpdateIntruders

This is run every update for the player's ship, and presumably also for
the enemy ship. This controls the enemies that are aboard the player ship.

This first sets all the crew to attack the system in the room they're in, or
gives them a bogus order to attack system SYS_INVALID (-1) if their room
doesn't have a system.

Next, it goes through each crewmember, using ChoosePriorityRoom to pick that
boarder's preferred room. It then commands that crewmember AND EVERY SUBSEQUENT ONE
to move to that room.

This means that the first crewmember picks the target for itself and all the
subsequent ones. They still run the loop, and if they see a better target (noting
that ChoosePriorityRoom returns the currently-assigned room if there's multiple
equally good options) they'll then re-assign themselves to that room.

This appears to be why enemies will meet up: one picks it's preferred room,
then all the others join it unless they have a reason to prefer a different system.


CrewAI::ChoosePriorityRoom

This uses PrioritizeIntruderRoom to calculate the priority of the room of our
currently-assigned task.

It then goes through all the rooms on the ship that aren't full and that we
can pathfind to, and uses PrioritizeIntruderRoom to find their priority.

If a room with a lower priority value (lower is more important) than the
currently-assigned room is found, switch to it. If there's multiple rooms tied
for lowest priority, pick one at random.

Note that the current task is kept if another task has the same priority - this
avoids the assigned room randomly switching constantly.


CrewAI::PrioritizeIntruderRoom

This picks the priority that is attached to a given room, for a given crewmember.

Ion intruder drones have special handling here (via crew->boardingGoal.damageType).
They return priority 1000 if there's no system in the room, and if the system
is ioned then it's treated as being fully broken.

The doors system is checked. If it's installed, and it's completely broken (or
possibly ioned) then the next step is skipped. This seems like a bug - I suspect
it was supposed to only check for blast doors.

Otherwise, if the crewmember can fight, the room being tested is the room the crewmember
is currently in, and there's enemies (from the point of view of the invading crewmember)
in the room, then the room is given priority -10.

Next, the danger of the room is calculated, accounting for the crewmember's fire
resistance and whether they're anaerobic (Lanius):

       No Fire  Fire
Air       0      100
No air   70      170

The 'no air' threshold is 10%, not the 5% that crew start suffocating at.

A 5 point penalty is added for rooms that don't have the exact same number of slots
as the number of boarders.

For rooms that aren't adjacent to the current player's room, a 10 point penalty is added.

For ion drones, a 100 point penalty is then added if this is the room they last attacked.

It appears that crew have two modes in their boarding goal, set by BoardingGoal.target:

System mode (value 1), where a 20 point penalty is applied if there isn't a system
to attack, it's broken, or (in the case of ion intruders) is already ioned.
Crew mode (value 0), where a 20 point penalty is applied for rooms without crew.

It looks like system mode is used as standard, from cursory search I can't find
anything that uses crew mode.


CrewAI::UpdateCrewMember

First, this checks for fires and hull breaches in the friendly crew's
current room, and assigns them to work on this. Enemies are assigned
to damage systems, or fight friendly crew.

Next, if the crew isn't fighting, repairing, or moving (CrewMember::IsBusy),
there's a series of checks, in the following order:

* If healing, and <99% health, and the medbay isn't hacked, remain
  in the healing state.
* If teleporting (notably, standing there while the cooldown resets),
  then stay in the teleporting state unless the ship AI decides not
  to request a teleport (eg, you teleport in first).
* If not manning a system, switch to idle mode.
* If someone else is manning the room, go into idle mode.
* Otherwise, continue manning the room.

Otherwise, the crewmember keeps their current task.


CrewAI::AttemptToAssign

This is called by OnLoop for each task in sequence. The tasks aren't sorted.
Also note this is called AFTER UpdateCrewMember, so what's set here
will override that function.

It loops through all the friendly crew, and for each one:

* If the crewmember is currently doing the given task, exclude them. Since
  tasks aren't added by CheckForProblems if there's a crewmember already
  doing them, this doesn't force multiple crew to do the same task.
  This check is required so that multiple identical tasks can be registered,
  eg calling multiple crew to defend a single room from intruders.
* If the crewmember's room doesn't have any doors (flagship weapons), then
  exclude them to avoid jamming up the AI.
* Exclude crewmembers whose task is more important (lower priority number)
  than the task to be assigned.
* If the crewmember's current task is combat, repair, fire-fighting, or
  hull-breach repair, and they're in the same room as the task, assign
  them immediately and stop the function here.

Assuming no crewmembers satisfied that last condition, pick the crewmember
whose current task has the highest priority value (is the last important).
If there's a tie, pick the crewmember that appears first in the crew list.

The priority depends on the crewmember, as some tasks (eg combat, putting
out fires, etc) depend on the crewmember. When calculating the priority
in the code above, use the crewmember under consideration.

Check if the new task's priority (as seen by the best crewmember, as picked
above) is lower (not lower or equal!) than the priority of the new task, and
if so assign the task to the new crewmember. This ensures that crew don't
constantly switch between equally-important tasks.

Finally, if a combat task isn't assigned, and some of the crew are bad
at combat, the combat/race override is set to avoid de-prioritising combat
tasks for crew that are bad at it. Once set, this flag (bOverrideRace) remains
